body:
[NIFI-13533](https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/NIFI-13533)

This is tested/verified the easiest by setting up a DatabaseParameterProvider. I set up one that talks to a postgres db running in docker.

```bash
docker run --name my-pg -p 5432:5432 -it -e POSTGRES_PASSWORD=password -d postgres
```

then i seeded it with some data
```sql
drop table if exists public.parameters;

create table public.parameters(
	groupName varchar(50) not null,
	parameterName varchar(50) not null,
	parameterValue varchar(2000)
);

insert into public.parameters (groupName, parameterName, parameterValue)
values ('group1', 'g1.param1', 'one');

insert into public.parameters (groupName, parameterName, parameterValue)
values ('group1', 'g1.param2', 'two');

insert into public.parameters (groupName, parameterName, parameterValue)
values ('group1', 'g1.sub.param3', 'three');

insert into public.parameters (groupName, parameterName, parameterValue)
values ('group.2', 'g2.param1', 'one');

insert into public.parameters (groupName, parameterName, parameterValue)
values ('group.2', 'g2.param2', 'two');

insert into public.parameters (groupName, parameterName, parameterValue)
values ('group.2', 'g2.sub.param3', 'three');
```

Connected my DatabaseParameterProvider like so:
<img width="657" alt="Screenshot 2024-10-02 at 4 55 44 PM" src="https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/976f38da-5fd1-4c0d-9800-264561c39e14">

_Obviously you will need a DBCPConnectionPool controller service enabled that connects to this database._
